  "prompt": "What steps should I follow to find the mechanical advantage of a simple machine?",
  "response": "Here are the steps to find the mechanical advantage of a simple machine:\n\n1. Identify the type of simple machine (lever, pulley, wheel and axle, inclined plane, wedge, or screw)\n\n2. Measure or determine the input force (effort force)\n\n3. Measure or determine the output force (resistance force)\n\n4. Calculate mechanical advantage using the formula:\nMechanical Advantage (MA) = Output Force \u00f7 Input Force\n\n5. For some machines, you might also consider the distance traveled by input and output forces\n\n6. Double-check your measurements and calculations\n\n7. Express the mechanical advantage as a ratio or whole number\n\nExample:\n- Input force = 10 N\n- Output force = 50 N\n- Mechanical Advantage = 50 N \u00f7 10 N = 5\n\nNote: A mechanical advantage greater than 1 means the machine multiplies force, making work easier.",
